Spring 2024 CPSC 471-05 (20930) Syllabus

Computer Communications

California State University, Fullerton

Disclaimer: You may not distribute/post this syllabus without written permission from Dr. Mike Turi, Electrical and Computer Engineering Department, California State University, Fullerton.

I. Course Information

  1. Course Description from the CSUF University Catalog:

    Introduction to digital data communications. Terminology, networks and their components, common-carrier services, telecommunication facilities, terminals, error control, multiplexing and concentration techniques.

  2. G.E. Requirements:

    This class does not meet any CSU General Education requirements.

  3. Course Prerequisites:

    • CPSC 351: Operating System Concepts
    • Computer science or computer engineering major or minor
    • Or computer science or computer engineering graduate standing

    Technical understanding of a computer language and a technical proficiency in basic operating system concepts should correspond to the prerequisites of this course.

    Technical proficiency with using information technology, such as, but not limited to, Canvas and the CSUF online portal, Zoom videoconferencing, sending and receiving email, and personal computer file systems, is assumed.

  4. Student Learning Goals (students should be able to):

    1. Gain an understanding of the makeup of a computer network.

    2. Understand fundamental algorithms and protocols required for network transmission in different mediums.

    3. Demonstrate HW Performance Indicator: Demonstrate understanding of the architecture of computer hardware (i.e., CPU, memory, storage, etc.), low level programming (e.g., assembly), operating system, middleware, and computer communication protocols.

IV. Course Work and Grade Distribution

  1. Grade Distribution:

    The following grading distribution will be used for both undergraduate and graduate students in this course, however, as per UPS 411.100, graduate students, students in an M.S. program, need to complete additional work for grade evaluation in this course. If graduate students, students in an M.S. program, are enrolled in this course and use this course on a graduate study plan, then they must complete an additional homework assignment which will be offered to the class; if this is the case, undergraduate students may choose to complete this additional assignment for extra credit. If no graduate students are enrolled in this course and use this course on a graduate study plan, then this additional homework assignment will not be offered to the class.

    Percent Grade Category
    10% Homework Assignments
    30% Midterm Exam #1: Wednesday, February 28
    30% Midterm Exam #2: Wednesday, April 10
    30% Final Exam: Wednesday, May 15, 2024, 5:00-6:50 PM

  2. Homework Assignments:

    1. These assignments test student understanding and application of the concepts of our class.

    2. These assignments will be assigned approximately every three to four weeks and will be due on Wednesdays.

    3. These assignments will be discussed in lecture and posted via Canvas in advance of their due dates.

    4. Each assignment must be typed; any exceptions to submit handwritten or hand-drawn work will be described in the specific assignment.

    5. It is the student's responsibility to ensure that the correct file is submitted and uploaded to Canvas. Furthermore, anything submitted outside of Canvas, e.g., via email, will not be accepted or graded.

    6. Each assignment must be completed individually unless otherwise specified.

    7. It is imperative to stay up-to-date with our lectures and assignments. Late assignments are accepted up to 48 hours past the due date, but with a 0.4% score penalty per hour; e.g., approximately a 10% penalty will occur if an assignment is turned in 24 hours late and approximately a 20% penalty will occur if an assignment is turned in 48 hours late. Note that this penalty will be calculated from the maximum value of an assignment; e.g., if you submit a 20-point assignment 10 hours late, then 0.8 points (4%) will be deduced regardless of your score, however, the minimum score for an assignment is 0 (there are no negative scores). Late assignments will not be accepted after 48 hours past the due date and will receive a zero.

  3. Midterm and Final Exams:

    1. We will have two in-person midterm exams on Wednesday, February 28 and Wednesday, April 10. We will have one in-person final exam on Wednesday, May 15, 2024, 5:00-6:50 PM.

    2. Note that this course is naturally comprehensive; concepts in this course will build off earlier concepts. Thus, midterm exam #2 may include concepts from midterm exam #1 and the final exam may include concepts from midterm exams #1 and #2.

  4. Make Up Work:

    An exception to submit a late homework assignment or to receive a makeup exam due to exceptional circumstances (e.g., a personal medical emergency, a family crisis, etc.) will be made on a case by case basis, provided the student informs the instructor preferably prior to the deadline, or at least within one week after the deadline.

  5. Extra Credit:

    Extra credit, if any, will be announced during the semester and be made available to all students. No assignments or extra credit will be assigned or due after our final exam time (Wednesday, May 15, 2024, 5:00-6:50 PM).

V. Grading

  1. Letter Grades:

    In this course the plus/minus grading system will be used. The grade breakdown is as follows:

    • A+ = 97 - 100%
    • A = 93 - 96.99%
    • A- = 90 - 92.99%
    • B+ = 87 - 89.99%
    • B = 83 - 86.99%
    • B- = 80 - 82.99%
    • C+ = 77 - 79.99%
    • C = 73 - 76.99%
    • C- = 70 - 72.99%
    • D+ = 67 - 69.99%
    • D = 63 - 66.99%
    • D- = 60 - 62.99%
    • F = 0 - 59.99%

  2. Final Course Grade Calculations:

    1. Course grades are computed by first finding the average percentage score in each grade category, then a weighted average is computed following the weights of the grading distribution.

    2. You may calculate your final course grade by reviewing your graded assignments and/or scores posted on Canvas.

    3. After the end of the semester the weights of the grading distribution may be adjusted to improve final course grades. If this occurs, new weights will be applied to each student equally and the final course grade will be the higher grade from the original weights or the new weights; please note that adjustments to the grading distribution weights will not be announced to the class.

    4. Lastly, please remember that final letter grades will appear on TitanOnline, not on Canvas.

  3. Grade Disputes:

    1. Any student disputes about graded assignments must be made in writing via email or Canvas message.

    2. A grade dispute must specifically identify the grading error(s); e.g., cannot ask to reevaluate the entire assignment.

    3. The grade dispute must be submitted within one week after the assignment was returned to students; you are not permitted to wait until the end of the semester to bring any or all assignments to dispute.

    4. Timely review of your graded assignments, available via Canvas, will reduce the likelihood of final course grade disputes/discrepancies at the end of the semester.

      However, any student disputes about final course grades must be made in writing via email and brought to the instructor's attention within "60 calendar days of the first day of classes of the regular semester following the award of the original grade;" the instructor will follow the policy defined by UPS 300.023.

If you miss a lecture, then it is your responsibility to find out what was covered and understand this material; you can do this by reviewing the course announcements, reaching out to a classmate, etc. However, there are times that you should not attend; do not attend if:

      1. You are feeling ill; this may put your classmates, myself, and other members of our campus at risk. If you have tested positive for COVID-19 and believe that you may have had it while you were on campus and/or in lecture, then notify me and use the CSUF self-reporting form.

      2. You have tested positive for COVID-19, even if you feel okay. Even if you have no symptoms, i.e., are asymptomatic, you may put others at risk. If you believe that you may have had it while you were on campus and/or in lecture, then notify me and use the CSUF self-reporting form.

      3. You are aware that you were significantly exposed to COVID-19 or another illness, then do not attend; use your best judgment with determining this.

      4. Likewise, if I am ill or COVID-19 exposed or positive, then I must cancel lab. If this happens, then I will send a Canvas announcement to the class outlining course changes.

  2. Social Distancing and Facemasks:

    1. You must adhere to any active social distancing and facemask policies when on campus.

VIII. Expected Course Conduct and Communication

  1. Conduct:

    1. As members of an academic community, it is our responsibility to provide a safe, inclusive classroom environment that is considerate of others, encourages exploration of ideas, and allows opportunities for everyone to fully engage in classroom discussions, activities, lectures, etc.

    2. To accomplish this, I ask that each of us refrain from conduct that is disrespectful and/or distracting to others in the classroom.

    3. The instructor expects…

      • Students will provide a safe, inclusive, classroom environment as described above
      • Students will refrain from:
        • Disruptive behavior during the lectures; if the lecture is being held virtually via Zoom, then please mute your microphone unless you wish to speak
        • Aggressive, threatening, or demeaning behavior towards other students or the instructor

    4. Students can expect…

      • The instructor will provide a safe, inclusive, classroom environment as described above
      • The instructor will ensure appropriate conduct during lecture
      • The instructor will report and ask students to leave who are excessively causing classroom misconduct or disruptive behavior that adversely affects the learning environment

  2. Communication:

    1. There are multiple ways to communicate with the professor during this course; these include:

      1. During our lecture:

        1. This is the best time to ask questions about our course topics or assignments. Often other students may have the same question(s) as you and will benefit by you bringing up this question(s) during our class time.

        2. This is not a good time to ask questions specific to your work on an assignment; my office hours are a better time to do this.

        3. You will also have minimal delay getting your question(s) answered during lecture.

        4. Note that asking questions during lecture will require that you arrive prepared and organized.

      2. During my office hours:

        1. This is a good time to ask questions about our course topics or assignments.

        2. This is a great time to ask questions specific to your work on an assignment.

        3. At times, it may be busy when trying to meet with me during my office hours, but typically, you will have only a short delay getting your question(s) answered during my office hours.

        4. Note that asking questions during my office hours will require that arrive prepared and organized.

      3. Immediately before or after our lecture or lab:

        Due to the scheduled time of our lecture, I will not have much time prior to or after our lecture.

        1. This is not a good time to ask questions about our course topics or assignments; it is much better to ask during our lecture (see Part i above for more details).

        2. This is not a good time to ask questions specific to your work on an assignment; I will have more time available during my office hours.

        3. While you will not have much delay in getting your question(s) answered, I will only be able to answer a short question(s) immediately before or after our lecture.

        4. Depending on your question(s), I may request that you instead ask your question(s) during lecture so that the entire class can benefit.

      4. Via email or Canvas message:

        1. This is an acceptable way to ask questions about our course topics or assignments, and it is the only way to contact me outside of our lecture, but it is much better to ask during our lecture (see Part i above for more details).

        2. This is an acceptable way to ask questions specific to your work on an assignment, and it is the only way to contact me outside of our lecture, but it may be better to ask during my office hours. It is often easier to explain your question(s) in person, especially when it involves your work with an application or code.

        3. You may experience a bit of delay when getting your question(s) answered via email or Canvas message; I do not constantly check my email or Canvas inboxes. I will typically respond to messages within 48 hours during business hours (8 AM to 5 PM, Monday-Friday), excluding holidays/breaks.

        4. If sending me an email, you must include the course number (CPSC 471) in the subject line; this helps me locate your email in my inbox. If you do not do this, then I may be delayed in seeing your email or I may not find it.

        5. When sending me an email or Canvas message, use an appropriate salutation (e.g., "Dear Dr. …" or "Hello Prof. …") and an appropriate closing (e.g., "Thank you, Anna" or "Have a good evening, Bill"). Please refrain from sending me email "texts".

        6. If sending me an email or Canvas message to request a Zoom meeting, then propose a few days/times you wish to meet and briefly explain the nature of the meeting; i.e., what class questions you have, etc.; failure to do this will result in no response or a delayed response.

        7. Depending on your question(s), I may request that you instead ask your question(s) during lecture so that the entire class can benefit.

      5. Do not call me on my office phone. I rarely use it and rarely check it for messages.

    2. The instructor expects that students will check their CSUF email and our course Canvas page on a regular basis for the duration of the course. Students will also check Canvas announcements on a regular basis for the duration of the course; students can configure how these announcements are received (via email, via text message, etc.) via their Canvas settings. Lastly, students will submit assignments using Canvas.

    3. Students can expect that the instructor will send announcements/updates via Canvas and post assignments, assignment deadlines, and lecture notes via Canvas.

X. Policy on Academic Dishonesty and Redistributing Class Materials or Resources

  1. Academic dishonesty includes such things as cheating, inventing false information or citations, plagiarism, and helping someone else commit an act of academic dishonesty. It usually involves an attempt by a student to show a possession of a level of knowledge or skill, which the student in fact does not possess.

    1. Cheating is the act of obtaining or attempting to obtain credit for work by the use of any dishonest, deceptive, fraudulent, or unauthorized means.

    2. Plagiarism is the act of taking the work of another and offering it as one's own without giving credit to that source; this includes the use of AI.

  2. The basic principle is that each student is expected to turn in his/her own original work and maintain a high standard of academic integrity.

    1. Attempting to take credit for someone else's work by turning it in as your own constitutes academic dishonesty and is a serious violation of CSUF's academic standards.

    2. Please familiarize yourself with the CSUF's academic dishonesty policy, which can be found in the current student handbook or in UPS 300.021.

    3. I recommend reviewing CSUF's Student Guide to Avoiding Plagiarism.

  3. Additionally, the instructor has created or received permission to use the class materials (i.e., assignments, quizzes, exams, etc.) and resources (i.e., lecture slides, handouts, examples) used in this course. Redistributing these materials or resources without prior permission from the instructor will violate the intellectual property (IP) rights of the instructor or owner of the materials/resources per the DMCA (Digital Millennium Copyright Act).

    1. A common example of redistributing class materials/resources and violating this policy is by posting an assignment on a third-party website such as Chegg, Course Hero, etc.

      1. This particular example also can result in a violation of the academic dishonesty policy; e.g., if you post an assignment on Chegg and use the solution provided by Chegg.

      2. To investigate these instances, note that CSUF can obtain account information from third-party websites to help the instructor identify who redistributed the class material/resource.

    2. If you wish to redistribute or reuse class materials or resources, then you must first receive written permission from the instructor.

    3. If class materials/resources are redistributed without permission from the instructor, then the penalty will be the same as academic dishonesty; a score of "0 (zero)" for the grade item and a possible final letter grade of "F" in the course along with an entry in the student records.

  4. There is no tolerance for academic dishonesty and redistributing class materials or resources without prior permission from the instructor; this policy will be strictly enforced. If you are academically dishonest and/or redistribute class materials or resources without prior permission from the instructor, then the following actions will occur:

    1. You will receive a score of "0 (zero)" for the entire grade item

    2. You will receive a final letter grade of "F" in the course if you have any prior violations of this policy in this course or your other courses

    3. You will be referred to CSUF Student Conduct

    4. You will be excluded from other extracurricular opportunities; e.g., I will not allow you to work on research projects with me, I will not write a letter of recommendation for you, etc.

  5. Students are encouraged to help each other as discussing material with others is a great way to study and learn. However, each student is expected to turn in his/her own original work, and clearly cite all resources including other students. Completing an individual assignment with a group of students and turning in copies of this group work is not permitted and is academically dishonest.

  6. In this class all assignments are individual assignments and must be done by the individual turning in the assignment. Files/code should not be transferred (e.g., email, printed, removable drive, scp, etc.) between you and any other student for any reason.

  7. Third party work (e.g., code, reports, AI-generated materials, etc.) may not be used in student work without prior instructor consent. When a third party's work is incorporated into student work after gaining instructor consent, the failure to properly cite the work will be considered as academic dishonesty.

  8. Protecting Your Work:

    Make sure that you protect your own work. Do not transfer (e.g., email, printed, removable drive, scp, etc.) any files/code between you and any other student. If you store your files on a public server, make sure the permissions are set so that only you can read them; ask your instructor if you don't know how to do this.

  9. If you have questions about what this policy means, please discuss this with the instructor now.
